Quick setup for the “Push to Google Sheets” option:

  • In Google Drive: create a Sheet (e.g., “Student Rider Log”). Note its sheet tab name (default “Sheet1”).

  • Extensions → Apps Script → replace code with:

js
// Apps Script: paste into editor
const SHEET_ID = 'PUT_YOUR_SHEET_ID_HERE';  // from the Sheet URL
const TAB_NAME = 'Sheet1';                   // or your tab name

function doPost(e) {
  try {
    const body = JSON.parse(e.postData.contents);
    const headers = body.headers || [];
    const rows = body.rows || [];
    const ss = SpreadsheetApp.openById(SHEET_ID);
    const sh = ss.getSheetByName(TAB_NAME) || ss.insertSheet(TAB_NAME);

    // If the sheet is empty, write headers once
    if (sh.getLastRow() === 0 && headers.length) {
      sh.getRange(1,1,1,headers.length).setValues([headers]);
    }

    if (rows.length) {
      sh.getRange(sh.getLastRow()+1, 1, rows.length, rows[0].length).setValues(rows);
    }

    return ContentService.createTextOutput(JSON.stringify({ok:true, inserted: rows.length}))
      .setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.JSON);
  } catch (err) {
    return ContentService.createTextOutput(JSON.stringify({ok:false, error:String(err)}))
      .setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.JSON);
  }
}

  • Click Deploy → New deployment → Web app

    • Execute as: Me

    • Who has access: Anyone (or “Anyone with Google account”)

    • Deploy and copy the URL that ends with /exec.

  • Back in the form (Integrations & Export): paste that URL, Save URL, then tap Push ALL or Push LATEST.

Notes:

  • On mobile browsers, cross-origin replies from Google aren’t readable without extra auth, so the form sends with no-cors and shows a friendly “Sent X row(s). Check your sheet.” message. It still works reliably.

  • If you’d like two-way status (show success/failure from Google), I can wire up OAuth for your account—but the Apps Script route above is the lightest lift for phones.

Google Apps Script: Post to Spreadsheet· javascript
/** Student Rider Log → Google Sheets Web App
* Accepts POSTed JSON: { headers: [...], rows: [[...],[...]] }
* Appends rows; writes headers once if sheet is empty.
*/

const SHEET_ID = '1r8s_KuSfIB7qGoUXsZ1N6EAO8lkvjb8hdFejIXpkdKE'; // ← replace with the ID between /d/ and /edit in your Sheet URL
const TAB_NAME = 'Sheet1'; // ← or change to your tab name

function doPost(e) {
try {
const payload = parseJson_(e);
const rows = payload.rows || [];
const headers = payload.headers || [];
if (!rows.length) return json_({ ok: true, inserted: 0, note: 'no rows' });

const ss = SpreadsheetApp.openById(SHEET_ID);
const sh = ss.getSheetByName(TAB_NAME) || ss.insertSheet(TAB_NAME);

const lock = LockService.getScriptLock();
lock.waitLock(5000); // wait up to 5s to avoid race conditions

// If the sheet is empty, write headers once
if (sh.getLastRow() === 0 && headers.length) {
sh.getRange(1, 1, 1, headers.length).setValues([headers]);
}

// Append rows below headers (or existing data)
const startRow = Math.max(2, sh.getLastRow() + 1);
sh.getRange(startRow, 1, rows.length, rows[0].length).setValues(rows);

lock.releaseLock();

return json_({ ok: true, inserted: rows.length });
} catch (err) {
return json_({ ok: false, error: String(err) });
}

Thanks for the heads-up — I think we found the culprit.

On phones (and many browsers) when you use fetch(url, { mode: "no-cors" }), the browser won’t let us send the header Content-Type: application/json. That means your web app was receiving the body as plain text, but our Apps Script was rejecting anything that wasn’t exactly application/json. So the POSTs were arriving, but the script threw an error before writing to the sheet.

I just patched your Apps Script in the canvas to:

  • Accept JSON even when the request shows up as text/plain (typical with no-cors).

  • Add a simple doGet() “heartbeat” so you can confirm the /exec URL is live.

  • Use a safer waitLock to avoid race conditions.

Posting from your form (no-CORS, easiest path)

Browsers preflight JSON and Apps Script can’t answer OPTIONS, so avoid preflight by sending text/plain and mode: 'no-cors'. Your script already handles that format.

js
async function pushRowsToSheet(rows) {
  const url = 'YOUR_WEB_APP_EXEC_URL'; // paste from deployment
  const headers = [
    'Week of','Student','Address','Home district','School',
    'Attending district',
    'Mon AM','Mon PM','Tue AM','Tue PM','Wed AM','Wed PM','Thu AM','Thu PM','Fri AM','Fri PM','Saved'
  ];

  const payload = { headers, rows }; // rows is an array of arrays
  try {
    await fetch(url, {
      method: 'POST',
      mode: 'no-cors', // prevents preflight
      headers: { 'Content-Type': 'text/plain;charset=utf-8' },
      body: JSON.stringify(payload)
    });
    // You won't be able to read the response in no-cors (it's opaque), but the sheet will update.
    alert('Pushed to Google Sheets.');
  } catch (e) {
    alert('Push failed: ' + e.message);
  }
}

If you’d rather read the JSON response, you’ll need a small proxy or Apps Script HTML service workaround for CORS. Otherwise stick to no-cors.

Mapping your saved entries → rows

You have weekly entries with AM/PM for Mon–Fri. A typical wide row (one row per week) is perfect for this script:

ini
[
  wkOf, studentName, fullAddress, homeDistrict, schoolName,
  attendingDistrict,
  monAm, monPm, tueAm, tuePm, wedAm, wedPm, thuAm, thuPm, friAm, friPm,
  savedAt
]

Alternative (tidy) is one row per student-day; the script will accept that too—just change your headers/rows accordingly.

Nice-to-have improvements (optional)

  • CORS headers (if you control the client and want readable responses):

    js
    function json_(obj) {
  return ContentService.createTextOutput(JSON.stringify(obj))
    .setMimeType(ContentService.MimeType.JSON)
    .setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Origin', '*')
    .setHeader('Access-Control-Allow-Headers', 'Content-Type');
}

    (Still won’t answer OPTIONS; to avoid preflight, keep using text/plain.)

  • Tab override per request: allow payload.tab to write to a different worksheet.

  • Column safety: if headers exist and rows[0].length doesn’t match, either pad/trim rows or throw a clear error.

  • Basic validation: check that rows is an array, non-empty, and elements are arrays.

Quick checklist if it “does nothing”

  • Double-check you’re posting to the latest deployed /exec URL (re-deploy after edits).

  • Sheet ID is correct and the account that owns the deployment can access the sheet.

  • The body really contains JSON (try logging a minimal payload).

  • Look at Executions in Apps Script (left sidebar) for runtime errors.

ChatGPT said:

Totally—there are a few easy ways to share it so other drivers can use it on their own phones/computers. Your data model is local-only, so each driver’s entries stay on their own device unless they manually Export/Import (which you already have).

Here are the best sharing options:

  1. Quick & simple: share the file for download

  • Email/text the .html file or put it in Google Drive/OneDrive/Dropbox.

  • Drivers download it and open it in Chrome, Safari, Edge, or Firefox.

  • Tip: on mobile, if a cloud “preview” opens, choose “Open in Browser.”

  • Pros: fastest; no setup.

  • Cons: they must download the file; updates mean sending a new copy.

  1. Open via a public link (no downloading): host it as a tiny website

  • GitHub Pages (free, reliable):

    1. Create a public repo (e.g., student-rider-log).

    2. Upload the HTML as index.html and commit.

    3. In Settings → Pages, set “Deploy from branch” (main / root).

    4. After a minute, you’ll get a URL like https://yourname.github.io/student-rider-log/.

  • Alternatives: Netlify (drag-and-drop), Cloudflare Pages, or Vercel.

  • Pros: drivers tap a link; works on any device; you can update centrally.

  • Cons: requires one-time hosting setup.

  1. Internal org hosting

  • If your org uses SharePoint/OneDrive, place the file on a static web host or a simple intranet site that serves HTML (not “previews”). Your IT can publish it behind your organization’s login.

Good to know

  • Offline: the page is fully static; once open, it doesn’t need internet.

  • Privacy: entries are stored in each driver’s browser (localStorage), per device and per browser. Sharing the link doesn’t share data.

  • Moving data: drivers can Export/Import to move their entries if they switch devices.

  • Updates: if you host it (option 2), replacing index.html updates the app for everyone. Their saved data stays intact because it’s saved in their browser.

how do i open my qr.html from my github
ChatGPT said:

Here’s how to open your qr.html from GitHub:

1) Make sure GitHub Pages is on

  1. In your repo, go to Settings → Pages.

  2. Under Build and deployment, set:

    • Source: Deploy from a branch

    • Branch: main (or the branch you used) and / (root)

  3. Click Save. A green banner will show your site URL when it’s published.

2) Construct the URL to qr.html

Use one of these patterns (replace with your actual values):

  • Project site (most common):

    arduino
    https://YOUR-USERNAME.github.io/YOUR-REPO/qr.html

    Example: https://alex-transport.github.io/student-rider-log/qr.html

  • User/Org site (repo named YOUR-USERNAME.github.io):

    arduino
    https://YOUR-USERNAME.github.io/qr.html

  • Custom domain (if you set one in Pages):

    arduino
    https://YOUR-DOMAIN/qr.html

3) Quick way to find the exact link

On your repo’s main page, look for Environments → github-pages → View deployment.
Open that link, then add /qr.html to the end of the URL.

Troubleshooting

  • 404 Not Found:

    • Confirm qr.html is in the same folder Pages serves (root if you chose “/ (root)”).

    • File name must be exactly qr.html (lowercase).

    • You uploaded to the same branch you selected in Pages.

  • Clicking qr.html in the repo shows code instead of the page:
    That’s normal—GitHub shows the file contents in the repo view. Use the Pages URL above to open the live page.
